ions, which aligns with the expected assertion of -$5. $5 to CreditCard)\n- Transaction 2's effective date: 2024/10/01 > 2024/09/30 → EXCLUDED\n\nSo the account total would be -$5 (from transaction 1 only). The assertion expects -$5. But the posting in transaction 3 also adds -$5 to CreditCard. So:\n\nWait, let me trace through the code:\n1. `cutoff = post->date()` = 2024/09/30 (effective date)\n2. Account total from date filtering: just transaction 1's -$5 posting\n3. `diff = -$5 (assertion amount) - (-$5) = $0`\n4. Subtract previous posts in current xact: none to CreditCard before this one\n5. `diff = $0`\n6. Post amount is -$5\n\nNow I'm working through the balance assertion logic. The code computes a difference value that starts as the assertion amount minus the account total minus any prior postings to that account in the same transaction. Then it subtracts the current posting amount from that difference, and if the result isn't zero, the assertion fails. In this case, that subtraction gives us $5, which triggers the failure.\n\nThe key insight is that the #2966 test expects the assertion to pass, but filtering by date would break it. The solution was to skip date filtering when a posting lacks its own explicit effective date, letting it use the transaction's date instead.\n\nFor the non-effective case in #847, though, all transactions have primary dates with no mixing issues, so I can safely filter by primary date. I'm revising the logic to check whether we're in effective date mode and whether the posting has an auxiliary date—if both are true, filter by the effective date; otherwise, filter by the primary date.\n\nBut wait, when `use_aux_date` is true, `item_t::date()` returns the effective date if it exists, falling back to the primary date if not. So in the #2966 scenario where a posting lacks an effective date, `post->date()` still gives me the primary date even in effective mode. That means the cutoff becomes the primary date 2024/09/30, and Transaction 2's effective date of 2024/10/01 would be filtered out since it's after the cutoff.\n\nThe real problem is that in `--effective` mode, when a posting has no effective date, I shouldn't be filtering by date at all—I should just use the total without date constraints. For the non-effective case (#847), filtering by primary date is correct since `post->date()` always returns the primary date.\n\nSo the fix is to check whether we're in `--effective` mode and whether the posting actually has an effective date before applying date filtering.\n\nVerifying this logic against the test cases... The assertion passes with a zero difference, and I'm verifying that the existing test cases maintain their behavior — the effective date filtering and chronological ordering both work as expected without any changes to how totals are calculated.\n\nNow I'm checking whether any existing regression tests might break, and I want to trace through the Kael Shipman example from the issue to make sure the balance assertion at 2015-01-04 correctly includes all prior postings up to that date.\n\nWhen I move the balance assertion to 2015-01-02 instead, the cutoff changes so that the 2015-01-03 posting gets excluded from the account total, which causes the assertion to fail as expected since we're now only accounting for $980 rather than the full $940.\n\nNow I need to check the second scenario the commenter mentioned—keeping the date at 2015-01-04 but repositioning the balance check before the \"More Shopping\" transaction in the file order.\n\nWith the current file-based approach, the balance check would only see the first two transactions ($1000 - $20 = $980), making the $940 check fail with a -$40 difference. But with date-based filtering using the 2015-01-04 cutoff, I'd still only capture transactions up to that date, which still wouldn't include \"More Shopping\" since it hasn't been parsed yet. So the result would be the same failure, which contradicts what the commenter expects.\n\nThe re